snippet.textDisplay:
I have to say I don’t find a single Rolls-Royce available today attractive, at all. To be honest they’re almost hideous.

The old classic Rolls-Royces were beautiful and luxurious. The BMW-era has been rife with slab sided blocks on wheels that don’t look like they should cost nearly their price tags.

And then they release this turd. Some genius didn’t get it classified as an SUV so you end up paying gas guzzler tax! The design is like a Range Rover, London Cabbie and Phantom all had a child and this is what was spit out and pimped out for a rapper’s music video. Those rims scream cheap aftermarket catalog, not $500,000.

snippet.textDisplay: RR is still the greatest luxury car maker in the world. Diversifying by building vehicles for varying markets have increased its revenue measurably and exposed its presence to ordinary folks, some of whom have become wealthy and would consider a RR for its quality as a more metropolitan or transitional vehicle. It’s no longer regarded as an a stuffy old man’s chauffeured car, and is sought by young wealthy athletes, producers, actors and ordinary rich persons in the private sector. The Rolls is better in every way imaginable, offering a multitude of modern conveniences using up-to-date tech and computer controlled systems that were unheard of 20 years ago. Ultra modern manufacturing have further refined the car that serves to elevate the marque combined with a dogged commitment to utter perfection. They’ve left no stone unturned and have thought of every conceivable way to improve the experience. No chauffeur for me however, I’d want to drive this amazing car.
